result.execSummary:
All charges against Mitchell A. Humbert in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Mitchell A. Humbert is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Mitchell A. Humbert appeared in court, Attorney Anthony Joseph Pozorski Sr. appeared in court for State of Wisconsin. Heard with case 21CF263. Court reviewes complaint, charges, penalties and right to counsel. Questioned about counsel. Morgan Sauder represents him in other county cases but he cannot afford her any longer. Requesting she be court appointed. Questioned about contacting other counsel. Court will not appoint Attorney Sauder. Defendant is sworn and testifies as to his financial situation. Court finds the Def. is indigent and appoints Attorney Mark Frank. Will defer reimbursement at this time, but when logging job is complete he should start reimbursing. PH set: 2/23/22 at 8:30 am.
